{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012rRjUK96pjMu3VYWDzGZDj","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Story 19.1: Epic Completion Detection\n2\t\n3\tStatus: review\n4\t\n5\t<!-- Note: Validation is optional. Run validate-create-story for quality check before dev-story. -->\n6\t\n7\t## Story\n8\t\n9\tAs a developer,\n10\tI want the engine to detect when all stories in an epic are done,\n11\tso that epic_flow tasks are triggered automatically.\n12\t\n13\t## Acceptance Criteria\n14\t\n15\t1. **Given** a new `src/lib/epic-completion.ts` module, **when** imported, **then** it exports `checkEpicCompletion(state, epicId): boolean`, `getEpicStories(state, epicId): string[]`, and `transitionEpicState(state, epicId, targetStatus): SprintState` functions. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n16\t\n17\t2. **Given** a sprint state where all stories in epic N have status `done`, **when** `checkEpicCompletion(state, epicId)` is called, **then** it returns `true`. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n18\t\n19\t3. **Given** a sprint state where at least one story in epic N does NOT have status `done`, **when** `checkEpicCompletion(state, epicId)` is called, **then** it returns `false`. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n20\t\n21\t4. **Given** an epic with status `in-progress` and all stories `done`, **when** `transitionEpicState(state, epicId, 'completing')` is called, **then** it returns a new state with the epic status set to `completing` and `storiesDone` updated to match `storiesTotal`. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n22\t\n23\t5. **Given** `getEpicStories(state, epicId)` is called with epicId `\"19\"`, **when** the sprint state contains stories `19-1-foo`, `19-2-bar`, and also `20-1-baz`, **then** it returns only `['19-1-foo', '19-2-bar']` — stories are matched by the numeric prefix before the first dash. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n24\t\n25\t6. **Given** the `EpicLifecycleStatus` type, **when** inspected, **then** it includes: `'in-progress'`, `'completing'`, `'merging'`, `'validating'`, `'done'`, `'failed'`. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n26\t\n27\t7. **Given** `transitionEpicState` is called with an invalid transition (e.g., `done` → `in-progress`), **when** executed, **then** it throws an `EpicCompletionError` with a descriptive message listing the current status and attempted target. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n28\t\n29\t8. **Given** the valid epic state transitions, **when** inspected, **then** they match: `in-progress → completing → merging → validating → done`, and `completing|merging|validating → failed`. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n30\t\n31\t9. **Given** an epic that does not exist in `state.epics`, **when** `checkEpicCompletion` or `transitionEpicState` is called, **then** it throws an `EpicCompletionError` with message indicating the epic was not found. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n32\t\n33\t10. **Given** an epic with zero stories in the sprint state, **when** `checkEpicCompletion` is called, **then** it returns `false` — an epic with no stories is never considered complete. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n34\t\n35\t## Tasks / Subtasks\n36\t\n37\t- [x] Task 1: Create `src/lib/epic-completion.ts` (AC: #1, #6, #8)\n38\t  - [x] Define `EpicLifecycleStatus` type with all six states\n39\t  - [x] Define `VALID_TRANSITIONS` map encoding the allowed state machine transitions\n40\t  - [x] Define `EpicCompletionError` class extending `Error`\n41\t  - [x] Export all types and functions\n42\t\n43\t- [x] Task 2: Implement `getEpicStories()` (AC: #5)\n44\t  - [x] Filter `state.stories` by epic ID prefix (extract epic number from story key pattern `{epicNum}-{storyNum}-{slug}`)\n45\t  - [x] Return array of matching story keys\n46\t\n47\t- [x] Task 3: Implement `checkEpicCompletion()` (AC: #2, #3, #9, #10)\n48\t  - [x] Validate epic exists in `state.epics`; throw `EpicCompletionError` if not\n49\t  - [x] Get stories for epic via `getEpicStories()`\n50\t  - [x] Return `false` if zero stories\n51\t  - [x] Return `true` only if ALL stories have status `done`\n52\t\n53\t- [x] Task 4: Implement `transitionEpicState()` (AC: #4, #7, #8, #9)\n54\t  - [x] Validate epic exists in `state.epics`; throw `EpicCompletionError` if not\n55\t  - [x] Validate transition is allowed via `VALID_TRANSITIONS`; throw `EpicCompletionError` if not\n56\t  - [x] Return a new `SprintState` with the epic's status updated (immutable — do not mutate input)\n57\t  - [x] Update `storiesDone` count when transitioning to `completing` (count stories with status `done`)\n58\t\n59\t- [x] Task 5: Write unit tests for `src/lib/__tests__/epic-completion.test.ts` (AC: #1-#10)\n60\t  - [x] Test: `checkEpicCompletion` returns `true` when all stories are `done`\n61\t  - [x] Test: `checkEpicCompletion` returns `false` when any story is not `done`\n62\t  - [x] Test: `checkEpicCompletion` returns `false` for epic with zero stories\n63\t  - [x] Test: `checkEpicCompletion` throws for non-existent epic\n64\t  - [x] Test: `getEpicStories` filters correctly by epic ID prefix\n65\t  - [x] Test: `getEpicStories` does not include stories from other epics\n66\t  - [x] Test: `transitionEpicState` returns updated state with new status\n67\t  - [x] Test: `transitionEpicState` updates `storiesDone` on `completing` transition\n68\t  - [x] Test: `transitionEpicState` throws on invalid transition\n69\t  - [x] Test: `transitionEpicState` throws for non-existent epic\n70\t  - [x] Test: `EpicLifecycleStatus` includes all six values\n71\t  - [x] Test: `VALID_TRANSITIONS` encodes the correct state machine\n72\t\n73\t## Dev Notes\n74\t\n75\t### Architecture Constraints\n76\t\n77\t- **Architecture Decision 6** (architecture-parallel-execution.md): Epic completion is deterministic — count done stories. The multi-step completion state (`completing → merging → validating → done`) gives the TUI and status command precise information about where the epic is in its lifecycle.\n78\t- **EpicState type** (`src/types/state.ts`): Current `EpicState` has `status: string`, `storiesTotal: number`, `storiesDone: number`. The new `EpicLifecycleStatus` type narrows the `status` field for lifecycle transitions. The existing `EpicState.status` is `string` (not a union) so the new type is compatible — the module should accept both the existing broad type for reads and validate narrower transitions.\n79\t- **SprintState V2** (`src/types/state.ts`): `SprintStateV2.epics` is `Record<string, EpicState>`. Stories live in `SprintStateV2.stories` as `Record<string, StoryState>`.\n80\t\n81\t### What This Story Actually Does\n82\t\n83\tThis story creates the **epic completion detection module** — a pure logic module with no side effects. It:\n84\t\n85\t1. **Detects** when all stories in an epic reach `done` status\n86\t2. **Provides** a state machine for epic lifecycle transitions (`in-progress → completing → merging → validating → done`)\n87\t3. **Filters** stories by epic ID from the sprint state\n88\t\n89\tThis module is a building block. It does NOT:\n90\t- Wire into the workflow engine (that's 19-2)\n91\t- Trigger epic_flow tasks (that's 19-2)\n92\t- Merge worktrees (that's already in worktree-manager.ts)\n93\t- Write state files (callers do that)\n94\t\n95\t### Key Files to Create\n96\t\n97\t| File | Why |\n98\t|------|-----|\n99\t| `src/lib/epic-completion.ts` | New module — epic completion detection + lifecycle state machine |\n100\t| `src/lib/__tests__/epic-completion.test.ts` | Tests for all detection and transition logic |\n101\t\n102\t### Key Files to Read (Do Not Modify)\n103\t\n104\t| File | Why |\n105\t|------|-----|\n106\t| `src/types/state.ts` | `SprintState` (V2), `EpicState`, `StoryState`, `StoryStatus` — the state types this module operates on |\n107\t| `src/lib/lane-pool.ts` | `EpicDescriptor`, `LaneStatus`, `EpicResult` — types used by the lane pool that will consume epic completion in 19-2 |\n108\t| `src/lib/worktree-manager.ts` | `WorktreeManager` — merge lifecycle that epic completion triggers (wired in 19-2) |\n109\t| `src/lib/telemetry-writer.ts` | `readTelemetryForEpic()` — used by retro step in epic_flow (wired in 19-2) |\n110\t| `src/lib/hierarchical-flow.ts` | `HierarchicalFlow`, `ExecutionConfig`, `BUILTIN_EPIC_FLOW_TASKS` — epic_flow structure |\n111\t\n112\t### Implementation Patterns\n113\t\n114\t**Story filtering by epic ID:**\n115\t```typescript\n116\texport function getEpicStories(state: SprintState, epicId: string): string[] {\n117\t  return Object.keys(state.stories).filter((key) => {\n118\t    const dash = key.indexOf('-');\n119\t    if (dash === -1) return false;\n120\t    return key.slice(0, dash) === epicId;\n121\t  });\n122\t}\n123\t```\n124\t\n125\t**Completion check:**\n126\t```typescript\n127\texport function checkEpicCompletion(state: SprintState, epicId: string): boolean {\n128\t  if (!state.epics[`epic-${epicId}`]) {\n129\t    throw new EpicCompletionError(`Epic epic-${epicId} not found in state`);\n130\t  }\n131\t  const stories = getEpicStories(state, epicId);\n132\t  if (stories.length === 0) return false;\n133\t  return stories.every((key) => state.stories[key]?.status === 'done');\n134\t}\n135\t```\n136\t\n137\t**State transition (immutable):**\n138\t```typescript\n139\texport function transitionEpicState(\n140\t  state: SprintState,\n141\t  epicId: string,\n142\t  targetStatus: EpicLifecycleStatus,\n143\t): SprintState {\n144\t  const epicKey = `epic-${epicId}`;\n145\t  const epic = state.epics[epicKey];\n146\t  if (!epic) throw new EpicCompletionError(`Epic ${epicKey} not found in state`);\n147\t\n148\t  const currentStatus = epic.status as EpicLifecycleStatus;\n149\t  const allowed = VALID_TRANSITIONS[currentStatus];\n150\t  if (!allowed?.includes(targetStatus)) {\n151\t    throw new EpicCompletionError(\n152\t      `Invalid transition: ${currentStatus} → ${targetStatus}`,\n153\t    );\n154\t  }\n155\t\n156\t  const storiesDone = targetStatus === 'completing'\n157\t    ? getEpicStories(state, epicId).filter((k) => state.stories[k]?.status === 'done').length\n158\t    : epic.storiesDone;\n159\t\n160\t  return {\n161\t    ...state,\n162\t    epics: {\n163\t      ...state.epics,\n164\t      [epicKey]: { ...epic, status: targetStatus, storiesDone },\n165\t    },\n166\t  };\n167\t}\n168\t```\n169\t\n170\t**Valid transitions map:**\n171\t```typescript\n172\texport const VALID_TRANSITIONS: Record<string, EpicLifecycleStatus[]> = {\n173\t  'in-progress': ['completing'],\n174\t  'completing': ['merging', 'failed'],\n175\t  'merging': ['validating', 'failed'],\n176\t  'validating': ['done', 'failed'],\n177\t};\n178\t```\n179\t\n180\t### Previous Story (18-3) Intelligence\n181\t\n182\t- Story 18-3 created `cross-worktree-validator.ts` — a focused extraction module (~120 lines). This story follows the same pattern: small, focused, pure logic.\n183\t- Testing pattern: vitest, `vi.mock`, colocated tests in `src/lib/__tests__/`.\n184\t- ESM module pattern: `.js` extensions in imports, TypeScript ESM.\n185\t- Build: `npm run build`, Test: `npm test`.\n186\t- All 124 tests passed after 18-3 with zero regressions.\n187\t- State builder helpers exist at `src/lib/__tests__/fixtures/state-builders.ts` — use `buildSprintState`, `buildStoryEntry`, `buildEpicState` for test data construction.\n188\t\n189\t### Git Intelligence\n190\t\n191\tRecent commits (18-1 through 18-3) established the merge lifecycle modules. This story builds on top of those by providing the detection logic that will trigger the merge flow in 19-2.\n192\t\n193\tFiles created in Epic 18:\n194\t- `src/lib/merge-agent.ts`\n195\t- `src/lib/cross-worktree-validator.ts`\n196\t- `src/lib/__tests__/merge-agent.test.ts`\n197\t- `src/lib/__tests__/cross-worktree-validator.test.ts`\n198\t\n199\t### Edge Cases\n200\t\n201\t- **Story key with no dash** (e.g., `\"orphan\"`): `getEpicStories` should not match — the `indexOf('-')` check returns -1, so the story is skipped.\n202\t- **Epic key format**: Sprint state uses `epic-{N}` as keys in `state.epics` (e.g., `epic-19`). Story keys use `{N}-{storyNum}-{slug}` (e.g., `19-1-epic-completion-detection`). The module must bridge this naming convention.\n203\t- **Multiple stories with same epic prefix but different total digits**: e.g., epic `1` vs epic `19`. Story `19-1-foo` must NOT match epic `1`. The filter must match the exact prefix up to the first dash.\n204\t- **Concurrent calls**: The module is stateless (pure functions over immutable data). Safe for concurrent use.\n205\t- **`state.stories` is empty**: `getEpicStories` returns `[]`, `checkEpicCompletion` returns `false`.\n206\t\n207\t### Boundary: What This Story Does NOT Include\n208\t\n209\t- **Wiring into the workflow engine** — 19-2 wires `checkEpicCompletion` into the engine's story-completion hook.\n210\t- **Executing epic_flow tasks** — 19-2 handles the retro → merge → validate sequence.\n211\t- **Persisting state transitions to disk** — callers (19-2) use `writeState()` from `state.ts`.\n212\t- **TUI display of epic lifecycle** — Epic 20.\n213\t- **Modifying `EpicState` type** in `src/types/state.ts` — the existing `status: string` is broad enough. The new `EpicLifecycleStatus` type narrows it for the module's own use.\n214\t\n215\t### Project Structure Notes\n216\t\n217\t- Source: TypeScript in `src/`, compiled to `dist/`\n218\t- Tests: vitest, colocated in `src/lib/__tests__/`\n219\t- ESM modules — use `.js` extensions in imports\n220\t- Build: `npm run build`, Test: `npm test`\n221\t- The `epic-completion.ts` should be a focused module (~80-120 lines). Pure logic, no I/O.\n222\t- Use state builder helpers from `src/lib/__tests__/fixtures/state-builders.ts` in tests.\n223\t\n224\t### References\n225\t\n226\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics-parallel-execution.md#Story 19.1]\n227\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-parallel-execution.md#Decision 6 -- Epic Completion Detection]\n228\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-parallel-execution.md#Epic State Transitions]\n229\t- [Source: src/types/state.ts#EpicState]\n230\t- [Source: src/types/state.ts#SprintStateV2]\n231\t\n232\t<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-START:story-verification -->\n233\t## Verification Requirements\n234\t\n235\t- [ ] Showboat proof document created (verification/19-1-epic-completion-detection-proof.md)\n236\t- [ ] All acceptance criteria verified with real-world evidence via docker exec\n237\t- [ ] Test coverage meets target (100%)\n238\t\n239\t## Documentation Requirements\n240\t\n241\t- [ ] Relevant AGENTS.md files updated\n242\t- [ ] Exec-plan created in docs/exec-plans/active/19-1-epic-completion-detection.md\n243\t\n244\t## Testing Requirements\n245\t\n246\t- [ ] Unit tests written for all new/changed code\n247\t- [ ] Coverage target: 100%\n248\t<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-END:story-verification -->\n249\t\n250\t## Dev Agent Record\n251\t\n252\t### Agent Model Used\n253\t\n254\tClaude Opus 4.6 (1M context)\n255\t\n256\t### Debug Log References\n257\t\n258\t### Completion Notes List\n259\t\n260\t- All 24 unit tests pass covering all 10 acceptance criteria\n261\t- Full suite: 4976 tests pass, 183 test files, zero regressions\n262\t- Module is ~120 lines, pure logic, no I/O — matches architecture constraints\n263\t- Follows existing patterns from cross-worktree-validator.ts and merge-agent.ts\n264\t\n265\t### File List\n266\t\n267\t- `src/lib/epic-completion.ts` — new module (epic completion detection + lifecycle state machine)\n268\t- `src/lib/__tests__/epic-completion.test.ts` — 24 unit tests covering all ACs\n269\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01KxDszVE1hewisgsfsHW1D6","session_id":"cb820906-0735-4f53-a851-3960824caad6","uuid":"43eed68f-a7ba-40a1-835b-1ff35240cf83","timestamp":"2026-04-03T22:59:36.892Z"}
